      <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;">
          <strong>🇫🇷 French PM survives no-confidence vote again</strong> 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">French Prime Minister Francois Bayrou survived two no-confidence votes after opposition parties <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-07-02-2025-br1-13-failed-to-secure" target="_blank">failed to secure</a> enough support to oust his minority government. The far-left introduced the motions after Bayrou invoked <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-07-02-2025-br1-14-article-49" target="_blank">Article 49.3</a> to push through a cost-cutting 2025 budget without a vote. While Bayrou avoided immediate removal, analysts predict his government may not last long and have estimated a 70% chance of collapsing in the coming months.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">The French constitution requires that parliamentary elections occur at least <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-07-02-2025-br1-15-one-year-apart" target="_blank">one year apart</a>, which means an election could be called as early as July 13th, 2025. President Macron faces ongoing political turbulence and is happy with the temporary stability, but tensions remain high as France prepares for further political challenges.</p>
        </mj-text>
