          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">What is the Grameen Bank?</h2>
        </mj-text>
         <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/what-is-the-grameen-bank.png" alt="Muhammad Yunus, the microcredit pioneer, delivers a speech" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
         <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
            Bangladeshi Nobel Peace Prize winner and microcredit pioneer Muhammad Yunus delivers a lecture at the Italian parliament. Credits: Andreas Solaro/ AFP
          </p>
        </mj-text>

        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
           <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;"><a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-07-02-2025-grameen-bank" target="_blank">Grameen Bank</a> is a microfinance organization and community development bank founded in Bangladesh by Nobel Peace Prize laureate and interim president Muhammad Yunus in 1983. He was inspired to make a loan to 42 families during the Bangladesh famine of 1974 and believed that a small loan could lift a lot of Bangladeshis out of poverty.</p>
           <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">These microloans enable borrowers to start or expand small businesses, improve living conditions, and build self-reliance. It helps its clients get a hand-up in the process of a handout. The bank employs an innovative group lending model that encourages mutual support, accountability, and shared responsibility among borrowers. This approach helps develop financial discipline and fosters community among its clients.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Grameen Bank has reduced poverty, making it a model for similar initiatives worldwide. It has improved lives by providing accessible financial services that can drive sustainable economic growth in underserved communities. However, it has not been without criticism; some say that microcredit is another way to trap some communities in debt.
          </p>
        </mj-text> 
